body:
Sometimes you automate some external screens, which can have same elements but with different IDs, texts, content-desc, etc. It's especially noticeable when you are automating tests on real devices from different vendors, with different OS versions, etc.

### Current implementation

For example, you have the one logical button but with 4 different locators due to environment changes:
```kotlin
val firstPossibleButton = UiButton { withId("packageName", "continue_button") }
val secondPossibleButton = UiButton { withId("packageName", "continue_redesigned_button") }
val thirdPossibleButton = UiButton { withId("packageName", "continue_new_button") }
val fourthPossibleButton = UiButton { withId("packageName", "continue_vendor_button") }
```

This declaration leads to complex appropriate checks in the test code:
```kotlin
compose {
    or (firstPossibleButton) { isDisplayed() } then { firstPossibleButton.click() }
    or (secondPossibleButton) { isDisplayed() } then { secondPossibleButton.click() }
    or (thirdPossibleButton) { isDisplayed() } then { thirdPossibleButton.click() }
    or (fourthPossibleButton) { isDisplayed() } then { fourthPossibleButton.click() }
}
```


### Proposed implementation

I think it will be nice to have an ability to declare the only one button which can be found with the help of different selectors, like this way:
```kotlin
val continueButton = UiButton {
    withId("packageName", "continue_button")
    or { withId("packageName", "continue_redesigned_button") }
    or { withId("packageName", "continue_new_button") }
    or { withId("packageName", "continue_vendor_button") }
}
```
As a result we have the only one button with simple usage in the test logic: 
```kotlin
continueButton {
    isDisplayed()
    click()
}
```
